Each @RequestMapping has a literal value string defining the path; I extracted those literal path strings exactly and converted path variables to brace notation as they appear in the annotations (e.g., {id}, {printShopID}).
- Each method mapped by a @RequestMapping was included as a separate API entry. Where the same path is used with different HTTP methods (e.g., POST and PUT on /printshops/{id}/pricetable/papers), I produced separate entries showing the differing httpMethod and handler method.
- All handler methods are implemented in the same source file (handlerPresentInFile = true).
- There is no class-level @RequestMapping in this file, so each extracted path is treated as the full mapping (pathIsPrefix = false).
- All paths are taken from literal strings in the source (pathExtractedFromLiteral = true); none are derived from naming conventions or inferred from other files (pathFromConvention = false).
- The controller is a REST controller (@RestController) so entries are marked isRest = true. None of the endpoints are test-only (isTest = false).
- I did not include any endpoints whose paths were not explicitly defined as literal strings in this file; no guesses were made about routes defined elsewhere.
